# Git Workflow & Commit Policy

# Commit Scope
- One commit per completed plan item. No more, no less.
- Keep commits atomic: one logical change per commit.
- Do not mix unrelated refactors with behavior changes.

# Commit Message Format
- Use Conventional Commits: `type(scope): description`
- Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `docs`
- Message must explain intent (why), not only file changes (what).
- Commit subject and body must be in English.
- Example: `refactor(core): migrate state module to src layout`

# What to Commit
- Source code: `src/`.
- Tests: `tests/`.
- Project metadata: `pyproject.toml`, lockfiles, team config.
- Documentation and planning: `docs/`, `.cursor/rules/`.
- Include updated `docs/PROGRESS.md` when archiving a completed plan wave (final commit of the wave or a dedicated `docs:` archive commit). Do not require `PROGRESS.md` changes on every intermediate commit while the active plan is still open.

# What NOT to Commit
- Runtime artifacts: `artifacts/` (screenshots, smoke outputs, temp files).
- Local environments and caches: `.venv`, tool caches, editor local state.
- Secrets and credentials: `.env`, tokens, keys, auth dumps.
- Never commit secrets even if accidentally staged.

# Pre-Commit Checks (Mandatory)
- Run targeted tests for changed behavior (unit first; smoke/integration when affected).
- Ensure `uv run ruff format --check` and `uv run ruff check src tests scripts` pass (config in `pyproject.toml`).
- Verify no unintended generated files are staged.
- If uncertain whether a file is runtime noise — do not stage it.